What does Cloud Composer manage that you had to do manually?
deploying airflow pod, manage rbac, use gcs for dag storage, use cloud sql (postgresql) for metadata db for airflow, install kubectl, handle pod  restarts, auto scale workers

Why is PostgreSQL better than SQLite for production Airflow?
SQLite doesn't run on servers and is very basic compared to PostgreSQL. including the mvcc and many things postgres is better and for airflow postgres is the gold standard.

Where are DAGs stored in Composer and how do they get picked up?
DAGs are stored in buckets inside dags folder and it is automatically synced into airflow by the composer

Why is trigger_rule="all_done" on delete_cluster?
so that even if a task fail, the cluster will get deleted

What is {{ ds_nodash }} in the cluster name?
it will give execution date and time with structured hyphens

Why create and delete cluster per DAG run instead of keeping one running?
composer clusters are expensive and need to be deleted to avoid high costs unnecessarily

What is the difference between Composer 2 and 3?
commposer 2 is the previous generation and only require service account as optional, networking is more stricter in composer 3